@node INTRO
@title "LastUser: Introduction"
@{b}INTRODUCTION@{ub}

   LastUser is a very simple MAXsBBS Door program that (when run!)
   will write the user name and time into a logfile. Information
   is appended to the file each time - thus a complete call log
   can be viewed.

   Why? Well, sometimes the BBS crashes (especially when you install
   a new game door function!) and the last user to use the BBS isn't
   stored in the caller log file. By simply noting the last crash time
   and looking in the lastuser logfile, you will be able to see who
   last used the BBS and thus start asking questions. Personally I have
   never had malicious users on my BBS and its always a new dodgy game
   door that has caused the crash......talking of which, I'm starting
   to write a few game doors myself (so the bug testing s/w has already
   been written! ;-) )

@endnode

@node INSTALL
@title "LastUser: Installation"
@{b}INSTALLATION@{ub}

   EASY! Just copy the LastUser program to your assigned doors: directory
   (and then copy this doc file somewhere if you _really_ need to keep it)

   You must also have bbs:logfiles/ directory!

@endnode

@node NEWSTUFF
@title "LastUser: New Stuff"
@{b}New Stuff@{ub}

   The program now actually works.. ;-)

   All data is appended to the logfile...this may be switchable in the future
   ..not sure yet..email me if you have any views about this.

@endnode


@node USE
@title "LastUser: Use"
@{b}Use@{ub}
  
   For this program to be of any use, you really need to run it very
   early in the log-in sequence. 

   I run it in the introdoor.text file -> this is found in the doors:
   directory. Edit the introdoor.text file (if it doesnt exist, make it!)
   and on the first line, write   LastUser
   
   Then save the file. When you next log in, LastUser will be run. I
   have NOT made any fancy messages for when the program is run -> there
   really is no need at all, this is meant to be some invisible SysOp
   debugging aid.

@endnode

